<UserControl xmlns="https://github.com/avaloniaui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
             xmlns:d="http://schemas.microsoft.com/expression/blend/2008"
             xmlns:mc="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/markup-compatibility/2006"
             mc:Ignorable="d" d:DesignWidth="800" d:DesignHeight="450"
             x:Class="StellarMVVM_2024.Views.interest_rates_archive_screen">
	<UserControl.Styles>
		<StyleInclude Source="/Styles/archive info styles/interest_rates_archive_stylesheet.axaml"/>
	</UserControl.Styles>
	<Panel Background="Pink">
		<StackPanel
			HorizontalAlignment="Center"
			Name="interestRatesArchiveStackPanel">
			<TextBlock
				Classes="title"
				PointerReleased="returnPrevious">
				interest rates
			</TextBlock>
			<TextBlock
				Classes="infoText">
				1. interest rates are associated with savings accounts and loans
			</TextBlock>
			<TextBlock
				Classes="infoText">
				2. for interests rates and loans, it is the percent of the loan you owe, in addition to the loan itself
			</TextBlock>
			<TextBlock
				Classes="infoText">
				3. for savings accounts, it is the percent of the money in the account that is added for keeping money in
			</TextBlock>
			<TextBlock
				Classes="infoText">
				4. interest rates can be compounded or simple
			</TextBlock>
			<TextBlock
				Classes="infoText">
				5. simple interest is the percent of the original money owed/put in (loan/savings). this amount is constant
			</TextBlock>
			<TextBlock
				Classes="infoText">
				6. compound interest is the percent of the money owed/put in at that moment in time, not the initial amount
			</TextBlock>
			<TextBlock
				Classes="infoText">
				7. for compound interest, the amount added to the principle value owed/put in usually increases
			</TextBlock>
			<TextBlock
				Classes="infoText">
				8. as a result, savings accounts with compounded interest grow a lot faster
			</TextBlock>
			<TextBlock
				Classes="infoText">
				9. on the other hand, loans with compounded interest are harder to pay off than simple interset
			</TextBlock>
			<TextBlock
				Classes="infoText">
				10. interest rates are a big part of finding the best loans/financial institutions
			</TextBlock>
		</StackPanel>
	</Panel>
</UserControl>
